WEBVTT

00:23.500 --> 00:25.940
CHAPTER 24.

00:25.940 --> 00:29.160
Miss Stacy and her pupils get up a concert.

00:30.640 --> 00:33.880
It was October again when Anne was ready to go back to school.

00:34.500 --> 00:40.040
A glorious October, all red and gold with mellow mornings, when the valleys were filled with

00:40.040 --> 00:44.600
delicate mists as if the spirit of autumn had poured them in for the sun to drain.

00:45.140 --> 00:48.260
Amethyst pearl, silver rose, and smoke blue.

00:49.460 --> 00:55.000
The dews were so heavy that the fields glistened like cloth of silver, and there were such heaps

00:55.000 --> 00:59.520
of rustling leaves in the hollows of many stemmed woods to run crisply through.

01:00.800 --> 01:06.280
The birch path was a canopy of yellow, and the ferns were sear and brown all along it.

01:06.980 --> 01:11.280
There was a tang in the very air that inspired the hearts of small maidens tripping,

01:11.420 --> 01:14.580
unlike snails, swiftly and willingly to school.

01:15.380 --> 01:19.660
And it was jolly to be back again at the little brown desk beside Diana,

01:19.660 --> 01:25.100
with Ruby Gillis nodding across the aisle, and Carrie Sloane sending up notes,

01:25.540 --> 01:28.800
and Julia Bell passing a chew of gum down from the back seat.

01:29.840 --> 01:32.680
Anne drew a long breath of happiness as she sharpened her pencil

01:32.680 --> 01:35.520
and arranged her picture cards in her desk.

01:35.980 --> 01:38.040
Life was certainly very interesting.

01:39.020 --> 01:42.100
In the new teacher she found another true and helpful friend.

01:42.800 --> 01:48.000
Miss Stacy was a bright, sympathetic young woman with the happy gift of winning and holding the

01:48.000 --> 01:52.420
affections of her pupils and bringing out the best that was in them mentally and morally.

01:53.540 --> 01:59.020
Anne expanded like a flower under this wholesome influence and carried home to the admiring Matthew

01:59.020 --> 02:02.840
and the critical Marilla, glowing accounts of schoolwork and aims.

02:03.660 --> 02:06.060
I love Miss Stacy with my whole heart, Marilla.

02:06.460 --> 02:09.280
She is so ladylike, and she has such a sweet voice.

02:09.760 --> 02:13.840
When she pronounces my name I feel instinctively that she's spelling it with an E.

02:14.320 --> 02:16.180
We had recitations this afternoon.

02:16.180 --> 02:20.220
I just wish you could have been there to hear me recite Mary, Queen of Scots.

02:20.540 --> 02:22.780
I just put my whole soul into it.

02:23.420 --> 02:26.240
Ruby Gillis told me coming home that the way I said the line,

02:26.660 --> 02:30.580
now for my father's arms, she said, my woman's heart farewell.

02:31.240 --> 02:33.180
Just made her blood run cold.

02:34.400 --> 02:38.780
Well now, you might recite it for me some of these days out in the barn,

02:39.160 --> 02:40.080
suggested Matthew.

02:41.200 --> 02:43.540
Of course I will, said Anne meditatively.

02:44.120 --> 02:46.820
But I won't be able to do it so well, I know.

02:47.500 --> 02:51.700
It won't be so exciting as it is when you have a whole schoolful before you,

02:51.720 --> 02:53.560
hanging breathlessly on your words.

02:54.380 --> 02:56.720
I know I won't be able to make your blood run cold.

02:58.000 --> 03:03.020
Mrs. Lynn says it made her blood run cold to see the boys climbing to the very tops of those big

03:03.020 --> 03:07.480
trees on Bell's Hill after crow's nest last Friday, said Marilla.

03:08.300 --> 03:10.940
I wonder at Miss Stacy for encouraging it.

03:11.580 --> 03:15.580
But we wanted a crow's nest for nature study, explained Anne.

03:16.080 --> 03:17.460
And that was on our field afternoon.

03:18.040 --> 03:20.240
Field afternoons are splendid, Marilla.

03:20.880 --> 03:23.500
And Miss Stacy explains everything so beautifully.

03:24.400 --> 03:28.640
We have to write compositions on our field afternoons, and I write the best ones.

03:29.840 --> 03:32.140
It's very vain of you to say so, then.

03:32.360 --> 03:34.460
You'd better let your teacher say it.

03:34.900 --> 03:36.800
But she did say it, Marilla.

03:37.220 --> 03:39.540
And indeed, I'm not vain about it.

03:39.540 --> 03:42.740
How can I be when I'm such a dunce at geometry?

03:43.840 --> 03:46.660
Although I'm really beginning to see through it a little, too.

03:47.180 --> 03:48.860
Miss Stacy makes it so clear.

03:49.660 --> 03:54.160
Still, I'll never be good at it, and I assure you it is a humbling reflection.

03:55.360 --> 03:57.160
But I love writing compositions.

03:57.920 --> 04:00.400
Mostly Miss Stacy lets us choose our own subjects.

04:01.000 --> 04:04.460
But next week we are to write a composition on some remarkable person.

04:05.340 --> 04:08.340
It is hard to choose among so many remarkable people who have lived.

04:09.040 --> 04:11.200
Mustn't it be splendid to be remarkable

04:11.200 --> 04:13.740
and have compositions written about you after you're dead?

04:14.580 --> 04:16.900
Oh, I would dearly love to be remarkable.

04:17.860 --> 04:20.640
I think when I'm grown up, I'll be a trained nurse

04:20.640 --> 04:24.220
and go with the Red Crosses to the field of battle as a messenger of mercy.

04:25.060 --> 04:27.840
That is, if I don't go out as a foreign missionary.

04:28.640 --> 04:30.320
That would be very romantic.

04:31.020 --> 04:33.440
But one would have to be very good to be a missionary.

04:33.880 --> 04:35.580
And that would be a stumbling block.

04:35.580 --> 04:39.540
We have physical culture exercises every day, too.

04:39.860 --> 04:41.980
They make you graceful and promote digestion.

04:43.580 --> 04:48.080
Promote fiddlesticks, said Marilla, who honestly thought it was all nonsense.

04:49.020 --> 04:51.620
But all the field afternoons and recitation Fridays

04:51.620 --> 04:53.440
and physical culture contortions

04:53.440 --> 04:56.840
paled before a project which Miss Stacy brought forward in November.

04:57.980 --> 05:01.680
This was that the scholars of Avonlea School should get up a concert

05:01.680 --> 05:03.900
and hold it in the hall on Christmas night.

05:03.900 --> 05:07.780
For the laudable purpose of helping to pay for a schoolhouse flag.

05:09.580 --> 05:12.440
The pupils, one and all, taking graciously to this plan,

05:12.880 --> 05:15.580
the preparations for a program were begun at once.

05:16.640 --> 05:21.220
And of all the excited performers elect, none was so excited as Anne Shirley,

05:21.920 --> 05:24.720
who threw herself into the undertaking heart and soul,

05:25.360 --> 05:27.720
hampered as she was by Marilla's disapproval.

05:28.600 --> 05:30.880
Marilla thought it all rank foolishness.

05:31.700 --> 05:34.020
It's just filling your heads up with nonsense

05:34.020 --> 05:37.120
and taking time that ought to be put on your lessons, she grumbled.

05:37.900 --> 05:41.720
I don't approve of children's getting up concerts and racing about to practices.

05:42.400 --> 05:45.700
It makes them vain and forward and fond of gadding.

05:46.420 --> 05:49.040
But think of the worthy object, pleaded Anne.

05:49.520 --> 05:52.700
A flag will cultivate a spirit of patriotism, Marilla.

05:53.720 --> 05:57.740
Fudge, there's precious little patriotism in the thoughts of any of you.

05:58.060 --> 05:59.920
All you want is a good time.

06:01.420 --> 06:05.620
Well, when you can combine patriotism and fun, isn't it all right?

06:06.500 --> 06:09.220
Of course, it's real nice to be getting up a concert.

06:09.800 --> 06:13.200
We're going to have six choruses and Diana is to sing a solo.

06:13.840 --> 06:18.800
I'm in two dialogues, the Society for the Suppression of Gossip and the Fairy Queen.

06:19.780 --> 06:21.820
The boys are going to have a dialogue too.

06:22.400 --> 06:24.500
And I'm to have two recitations, Marilla.

06:25.060 --> 06:27.160
I just tremble when I think of it.

06:27.460 --> 06:29.600
But it's a nice, thrilling kind of tremble.

06:30.240 --> 06:34.480
And we're to have a tableau at the end, faith, hope, and charity.

06:35.180 --> 06:39.980
Diana and Ruby and I are all to be in it, all draped in white with flowing hair.

06:40.640 --> 06:45.860
I'm to be hope with my hands clasped, so, and my eyes uplifted.

06:46.840 --> 06:49.180
I'm going to practice my recitations in the garret.

06:49.760 --> 06:51.720
Don't be alarmed if you hear me groaning.

06:52.060 --> 06:54.600
I have to groan heartrendingly in one of them.

06:55.020 --> 06:58.160
And it's really hard to get up a good artistic groan, Marilla.

06:59.100 --> 07:02.740
Josie Pye is sulky because she didn't get the part she wanted in the dialogue.

07:03.480 --> 07:05.040
She wanted to be the fairy queen.

07:05.760 --> 07:10.540
That would have been ridiculous, for who ever heard of a fairy queen as fat as Josie?

07:10.860 --> 07:12.620
Fairy queens must be slender.

07:13.700 --> 07:17.720
Jane Andrews is to be the queen, and I am to be one of her maids of honor.

07:18.600 --> 07:22.600
Josie says she thinks a red-haired fairy is just as ridiculous as a fat one.

07:22.920 --> 07:25.580
But I do not let myself mind what Josie says.

07:26.460 --> 07:29.060
I'm to have a wreath of white roses on my hair,

07:29.380 --> 07:33.080
and Ruby Gillis is going to lend me her slippers because I haven't any of my own.

07:33.920 --> 07:36.800
It's necessary for fairies to have slippers, you know.

07:37.180 --> 07:41.100
You couldn't imagine a fairy wearing boots, could you, especially with copper toes?

07:42.120 --> 07:45.660
We are going to decorate the hall with creeping spruce and fur mottos

07:45.660 --> 07:47.940
with pink tissue paper roses in them.

07:48.280 --> 07:51.660
And we are all to march in two by two after the audience is seated,

07:51.960 --> 07:54.080
while Emma White plays a march on the organ.

07:54.760 --> 07:58.720
Oh, Marilla, I know you are not so enthusiastic about it as I am,

07:58.980 --> 08:01.860
but don't you hope your little Anne will distinguish herself?

08:02.920 --> 08:05.380
All I hope is that you'll behave yourself.

08:05.820 --> 08:10.360
I'll be heartily glad when all this fuss is over, and you'll be able to settle down.

08:10.520 --> 08:12.360
And you are simply good for nothing just now,

08:12.400 --> 08:15.740
with your head stuffed full of dialogues and groans and tableaus.

08:16.520 --> 08:20.360
As for your tongue, it's a marvel, it's not clean worn out.

08:22.100 --> 08:27.200
Anne sighed and betook herself to the back yard, over which a young new moon was shining

08:27.200 --> 08:31.000
through the leafless poplar boughs from an apple green western sky,

08:31.320 --> 08:32.840
and where Matthew was splitting wood.

08:33.700 --> 08:37.220
Anne perched herself on a block and talked the concert over with him.

08:38.160 --> 08:41.900
Sure of an appreciative and sympathetic listener in this instance, at least.

08:42.860 --> 08:46.100
Well now, I reckon it's going to be a pretty good concert,

08:46.100 --> 08:49.720
and I expect you'll do your part fine, he said,

08:49.720 --> 08:52.660
smiling down into her eager vivacious little face.

08:53.440 --> 08:54.960
Anne smiled back at him.

08:55.140 --> 08:56.720
Those two were the best of friends,

08:56.980 --> 08:59.620
and Matthew thanked his stars many a time and oft

08:59.620 --> 09:02.220
that he had nothing to do with bringing her up.

09:02.680 --> 09:04.520
That was Marilla's exclusive duty.

09:05.160 --> 09:08.180
If it had been his, he would have been worried over frequent conflicts

09:08.180 --> 09:10.580
between inclination and said duty.

09:11.180 --> 09:16.500
As it was, he was free to spoil Anne, Marilla's phrasing, as much as he liked.

09:17.280 --> 09:19.700
But it was not such a bad arrangement, after all.

09:19.720 --> 09:23.320
A little appreciation sometimes does quite as much good

09:23.320 --> 09:26.100
as all the conscientious bringing up in the world.

09:27.960 --> 09:29.400
End of chapter 24

